Then verify it:

This setup has an important requirement:
Because the MCP server runs inside the Obsidian plugin, Obsidian must be running.
Use this path when you want the agent to interact through Obsidian-aware operations rather than only raw filesystem tools.
Path 3: Use Claudian inside Obsidian
Claudian embeds agent runtimes—including Claude Code—inside an Obsidian sidebar. Its documented capabilities include file reading and writing, search, shell execution, multi-step workflows, inline edits with word-level previews, planning, skills, and MCP integration. It is desktop-only and requires Obsidian 1.7.2 or later.
This is the most integrated experience:
• you write in Obsidian;
• the agent works in the same application;
• edits can be reviewed without switching tools;
•the vault becomes the runtime’s working directory.
It is a strong choice for interactive writing and research.
However, plugins add another dependency layer. Compatibility with new Claude Code releases should be checked before relying on it for critical workflows.

The most important configuration is not a note
In a Claude Code workflow, the highest-leverage file is often CLAUDE.md.
Claude Code loads CLAUDE.md as persistent project guidance. It is intended for instructions such as architecture, workflows, conventions, and behavioral rules. Anthropic also provides auto memory, stored in a separate memory directory with a concise MEMORY.md index loaded at the beginning of sessions.
These mechanisms serve different purposes.
CLAUDE.md
Written and maintained by you.
Use it for:
• the purpose of the vault;
• folder responsibilities;
• formatting conventions;
• write restrictions;
• citation rules;
• ingestion procedures;
• definitions of “source,” “note,” and “synthesis”;
• rules for handling contradictions;
• required approval before destructive actions.
Auto memory
Written by Claude from recurring discoveries, corrections, and preferences.
Use it for:
• operational lessons;
• frequently used commands;
• recurring preferences;
• project-specific patterns;
• debugging knowledge.
A useful knowledge-vault CLAUDE.md might begin like this:

That file turns a generic agent into a more disciplined vault maintainer.
Session amnesia is real—but the fix has evolved
Every Claude Code session begins with a fresh context window. Continuity can be handled through:
• persistent instructions in CLAUDE.md;
• auto memory with MEMORY.md and on-demand topic files;
• project-level session handoff notes.
For example:

This file is not model training. It is externalized state.
Claude does not permanently update its model weights by reading your vault. The system becomes more context-aware because it accumulates files, summaries, links, instructions, and memory that future sessions can read.
The intelligence is not “learning in the background” in the human sense. It is persistent context engineering.

From a vault to a persistent wiki
The deepest idea behind this architecture comes from Andrej Karpathy’s LLM Wiki pattern.
Karpathy proposes three layers:
Raw sources — immutable original material.
The wiki — LLM-generated Markdown pages containing concepts, entities, comparisons, and syntheses.
The schema — instructions such as CLAUDE.md or AGENTS.md defining how the agent should ingest, maintain, query, and lint the wiki.
When a new source arrives, the agent does not merely embed it for later retrieval.
It can:
• create a source summary;
• update existing concept pages;
• add or revise entity pages;
• create cross-references;
• record conflicting claims;
• update an index;
• add unanswered questions;
• log what changed.
The result is a persistent, evolving artifact rather than a transient answer in a chat window.
This does not make retrieval obsolete
It is misleading to describe persistent wikis as the opposite of RAG.
The stronger architecture combines them.
Raw RAG typically retrieves chunks from source material. A compiled wiki gives the agent an additional retrieval target: already synthesized, linked, and maintained pages.
A robust system can retrieve from:
• raw source documents for evidence;
• wiki pages for accumulated synthesis;
• session state for current work;
• project notes for user-authored interpretation.
The wiki changes what is retrieved. It does not eliminate the need for retrieval.
